SIMPLE: slip
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slip
<hw>Slip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Slipped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Slipping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>slippen</ets>; akin to
LG. & D. <ets>slippen</ets>, MHG. <ets>slipfen</ets> (cf. Dan.
<ets>slippe</ets>, Sw. <ets>slippa</ets>, Icel. <ets>sleppa</ets>), and
fr. OE. <ets>slipen</ets>, AS. <ets>sl⟦imac⟧pan</ets> (in comp.), akin
to G. <ets>schleifen</ets> to slide, glide, drag, whet, OHG.
<ets>sl⟦imac⟧fan</ets> to slide, glide, make smooth, Icel.
<ets>sl⟦imac⟧pa</ets> to whet; cf. also AS. <ets>sl<?/pan</ets>, Goth.
<ets>sliupan</ets>, OS. <ets>slopian</ets>, OHG. <ets>sliofan</ets>, G.
<ets>schliefen</ets>, <ets>schl<?/pfen</ets>, which seem to come from a
somewhat different root form. Cf. <er>Slope</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To move along the surface of a thing without bounding,
rolling, or stepping; to slide; to glide.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To slide; to lose one's footing or one's hold; not
to tread firmly; <as>as, it is necessary to walk carefully lest the foot
should <ex>slip</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To move or fly (out of place); to shoot; -- often
with <xex>out</xex>, <xex>off</xex>, etc.; <as>as, a bone may
<ex>slip</ex> out of its place</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To depart, withdraw, enter, appear, intrude, or
escape as if by sliding; to go or come in a quiet, furtive manner;
<as>as, some errors <ex>slipped</ex> into the work</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus one tradesman <qex>slips</qex> away,⟦br⟧
To give his partner fairer play.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thrice the flitting shadow <qex>slipped</qex> away.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To err; to fall into error or fault.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is one that <qex>slippeth</qex> in his speech, but not from
his heart.</q> <rj><qau>Ecclus. xix. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To let slip</b></col>, <cd>to loose from the slip or
noose, as a hound; to allow to escape.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cry, ⟦ldquo⟧Havoc,⟦rdquo⟧ and <qex>let slip</qex> the dogs of
war.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slip
<hw>Slip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause
to move smoothly and quickly; to slide; to convey gently or
secretly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He tried to <qex>slip</qex> a powder into her drink.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To omit; to loose by negligence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>slip</qex> no advantage⟦br⟧
That my secure you.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cut slips from; to cut; to take off; to make a
slip or slips of; <as>as, to <ex>slip</ex> a piece of cloth or
paper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The branches also may be <qex>slipped</qex> and planted.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To let loose in pursuit of game, as a
greyhound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lucento <qex>slipped</qex> me like his greyhound.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To cause to slip or slide off, or out of place;
<as>as, a horse <ex>slips</ex> his bridle; a dog <ex>slips</ex> his
collar</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To bring forth (young) prematurely; to
slink.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To slip a cable</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Cable</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To slip off</b></col>, <cd>to take
off quickly; <as>as, <ex>to slip off</ex> a coat</as>.</cd> --
<col><b>To slip on</b></col>, <cd>to put on in haste or loosely; <as>as,
<ex>to slip on</ex> a gown or coat</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Slip
<hw>Slip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>slipe</ets>,
<ets>slip</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of slipping; <as>as, a
<ex>slip</ex> on the ice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An unintentional error or fault; a false
step.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This good man's <qex>slip</qex> mended his pace to martyrdom.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A twig separated from the main stock; a cutting; a
scion; hence, a descendant; <as>as, a <ex>slip</ex> from a
vine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A native <qex>slip</qex> to us from foreign seeds.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The girlish <qex>slip</qex> of a Sicilian bride.</q> <rj><qau>R.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A slender piece; a strip; <as>as, a <ex>slip</ex> of
paper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Moonlit <qex>slips</qex> of silver cloud.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A thin <qex>slip</qex> of a girl, like a new moon⟦br⟧
Sure to be rounded into beauty soon.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A leash or string by which a dog is held; -- so
called from its being made in such a manner as to slip, or become loose,
by relaxation of the hand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We stalked over the extensive plains with Killbuck and Lena in the
<qex>slips</qex>, in search of deer.</q> <rj><qau>Sir S.
Baker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An escape; a secret or unexpected desertion; <as>as,
to give one the <ex>slip</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A portion of the columns of a
newspaper or other work struck off by itself; a proof from a column of
type when set up and in the galley.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Any covering easily slipped on.</def> Specifically:
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>A loose garment worn by a woman.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A child's pinafore.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>An outside covering or
case; <as>as, a pillow <ex>slip</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>The
<ex>slip</ex> or sheath of a sword, and the like.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A counterfeit piece of money, being brass covered
with silver.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Matter found in troughs of grindstones after the
grinding of edge tools.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir W.
Petty.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>Potter's clay in a very liquid state, used for the
decoration of ceramic ware, and also as a cement for handles and other
applied parts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>A particular quantity of yarn.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>An inclined plane on which a vessel is built, or
upon which it is hauled for repair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>An opening or space for vessels to lie in, between
wharves or in a dock; <as>as, Peck <ex>slip</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <def>A narrow passage between buildings.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <def>A long seat or narrow pew in churches, often
without a door.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>17.</sn> <fld>(Mining.)</fld> <def>A dislocation of a lead,
destroying continuity.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>18.</sn> <fld>(Engin.)</fld> <def>The motion of the center of
resistance of the float of a paddle wheel, or the blade of an oar,
through the water horozontally, or the difference between a vessel's
actual speed and the speed which she would have if the propelling
instrument acted upon a solid; also, the velocity, relatively to still
water, of the backward current of water produced by the
propeller.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>19.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A fish, the sole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>20.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>A fielder stationed on the off
side and to the rear of the batsman. There are usually two of them,
called respectively <stype>short slip</stype>, and <stype>long
slip</stype>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 21. A slip dock (see below) -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>22.</sn><fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The retrograde
movement on a pulley of a belt as it slips.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>In a
link motion, the undesirable sliding movement of the link relatively to
the link block, due to swinging of the link.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>23.</sn> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>The difference between the
actual and synchronous speed of an induction motor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>23.</sn> <fld>(Marine Insurance)</fld> <def>A memorandum of the
particulars of a risk for which a policy is to be executed. It usually
bears the broker's name and is initiated by the underwrites.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To give one the slip</b></col>, <cd>to slip away from
one; to elude one.</cd> -- <col><b>Slip dock</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Dock</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Slip link</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>,
<cd>a connecting link so arranged as to allow some play of the parts, to
avoid concussion.</cd> -- <col><b>Slip rope</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a rope by which a cable is secured preparatory
to slipping.</cd> <au>Totten.</au> -- <col><b>Slip stopper</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>an arrangement for letting go the anchor
suddenly.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slipboard</ent>⟦br⟧
